(4392, 148314, 'Jacob & Fabrice', 'Nonchalant yet au fait, Parisian duo Logo produces a techno that’s as shambolic as it is effective. Hughes and Thomas have two EPs under their belt, a bunch of remixes for the likes of Mark Ronson ft Pharell Williams, Black Devil disco Club and Yelle, not forgetting some well tailored edits offered to blogs and djs. Signed to the family-like Kitsuné Maison stable two years ago thanks to their first ever track ‘la Vie Moderne’, the pair’s already sailed the seven seas with Gallic dj companions such as Para One, Joakim, Brodinski, Club Cheval or Tom Trago, spreading their electrochic mentalism from Japan’s Summer Sonic festival to Spain’s Aquasella, Amsterdam Dance Event to France’s Calvi On The Rocks and Astropolis.\r\n\r\nEncounters, travels and other revelations have unquestionably driven their productions towards a mutating form of (intelligent?) techno as ever rich in well thought-out twists and details, expressed with candour, spontaneity and possibly more fluidity since they’ve experienced life on the road.\r\n\r\n‘Jacob & Fabrice’, their brand new EP to be released on Kitsuné May 21st is here to prove it. A proper double A side like they used to say. Two rather enormous tracks that compliment each other well . ‘Fabrice’ combines acid house, trance and tribal in one evil spell that will get most djs frothing at the mouth. The kind of track which dropped in the right place at the right time – preferably after-hours – will raise the roof off effortlessly. Not that ‘Jacob’ couldn’t compete, this dangerous weapon can virtually take any party to the next level with its endless God-like stabs from above. This is techno for NY dancefloors, or Liverpool’s or Rimini’s… a funky, racey trooper that owes a lot to the best vintage house and still sounds fresh, if not timeless. The boys have done us proud.\r\n\r\nRemix-wise, Crackboy delivers a jackin’ reinterpretation of ‘Fabrice’, liquid yet menacing, all cranked up to 11. On the same track, 5kinAndBone5, the two Californians off the Unknown To The Unknown imprint, turn out a barmy, wonky – dare we say it? – dubstep rerub aimed at the more alternative, rhythmically fractured dancefloors. Finally Darabi, opting for a futuristic Detroit angle on ‘Jacob’, smoothes corners out with weird jazzy chords and soulful Prince-ish whispering.', '2012-05-21 00:00:00', 0, 2, 3, '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, '2012-05-21 17:16:28', '2015-02-16 15:48:13', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
